Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law on administrative liability for violation of the time and procedure for payment of goods (work, services) in procurement for public and municipal needs.
The Act is intended to address the very acute problem of non-performance by customers in public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation where entrepreneurs could not receive payment under State and municipal contracts already executed was widespread.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Office of the Procurator-General of the Russian Federation to take special control of the problem.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with bad-faith employers who entered into unfunded contracts, tried to evade their obligations to pay and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, the Public Prosecutor ' s Office has made 9,700 submissions, disciplinary proceedings have resulted in the prosecution of 4,500 officials, administrative proceedings have been instituted against 533 persons, and investigations have been conducted with 75 materials for the conduct of procedural checks, and criminal proceedings have been initiated against 46 of them.
As a result, more than 66 billion rubles were repaid to entrepreneurs.
These huge amounts were not accumulated as a result of the non-payment of multi-billion-dollar contracts.
Many, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts have led to massive debts.
Here's the specific case.
The head of a small company won a competition for several million roubles in social transport services.
The person invested all of his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is an increasing financial combo of wages, taxes, loans that would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought assistance from the prosecutor's office.
The problem has now been reduced as much as possible in a number of regions.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt on State and municipal contracts identified by the procurators of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation was about 27.4 billion roubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical levels, the Public Prosecutor ' s Office operates under a manual crisis management regime.
The Attorney-General personally holds field meetings with the local authorities, at which all violations discovered by prosecutors are dealt with in a substantive manner and measures taken to remedy them immediately.
Such operational meetings have already taken place in Jaroslavla and Yekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On the amendment of the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation with regard to the establishment of administrative liability of the employer's officials for the violation of the time and procedure for the payment of goods (work, services) in procurement to meet State and municipal needs", signed last week by the President of the Russian Federation, will improve the payment discipline of public customers.
The draft law was prepared by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Office of the Procurator-General.
The new law will supplement the Russian Code of Administrative Offences with an article which provides for a fine of between 30,000 and 50,000 roubles for the violation by the employer ' s official of the time and procedure for the payment of goods, works and services in State and municipal procurement.
If an official has already been subject to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he or she will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure that these legislative innovations are applied in practice.
