Bardin Degei doesn't use a stove when preparing dinner.
She doesn't even use a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarothali, the capital of Paniai County in the rebel Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually simply places sweet potatoes, which is called a note, right in the middle.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the ground floor – she doesn't have any furniture – and this is where she does her homework, such as washing her clothes with murky water from nearby marshes.
The bathroom is a bucket in a room without a roof.
She's the youngest of her husband's four wives, so she wasn't assigned to work in the field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late may be dangerous: many men from this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
"No one decides to walk in the village after 5:00 p.m.," she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at daily life in the highlands of Papua, the former Dutch colony, which was attached to Indonesia in 1969 after a questionable referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, raising their hands in public before the occupying forces.
The current movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta Government, which maintained strict control over the region by preventing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, while the independent State of Papua New Guinea occupied the eastern part of the island.
Enarothali is a city as remote as an abandoned one; the road includes an hour and a half flight from Jayapura, the provincial capital, to Nabira, and then a five-hour shaking by a hired car.
