Morse Ford's murder: activists will lose Lynch's courts on stage to call for justice.
"Ford Mercury" of 1948 passed the audience in the village of Monroe, Georgia, and racing towards the little bridge Morse Ford.
When the car, which had four black passengers and a white driver, approached the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked its way.
The leader, a middle-aged man wearing a thin stripe, took a cigar and looked through the windshield.
Sitting inside was shaking in fear.
"We need this nigger, Roger!" a man buzzed.
"Get him out of the car!"
Shouting screams ripped the silence when a young black man was dragged out of the front seat.
Fortunately, this terrible scene, which was played on July 22, is just a stage.
But when Roger's neck was covered with a noose, most of the audience actually held their breath.
Since 2005, activists have returned to the Morse Ford Bridge to lose again that night when in 1946 the dollexklanians lynched two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and May Murray Dorsey.
No one was convicted of these murders.
"It's amazing that no one has been arrested in all these years - although we see them with us; although we know who they are," says Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the play.
"It's a stain on our history and it's a rock on our souls."
71-year-old Brooks is a former member of the Congress of Georgia who has been fighting for human rights all his life.
To him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to Monroe residents that injustice has never been corrected.
"We want an investigation, we want an end, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice," he says.
"We cannot proceed to healing and reconciliation until justice is done."
The coroner covers the body of one of the lynching victims at Morse Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI records received by Al-Bse News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighbouring counties were suspected of involvement in lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
Although the suspects have remained at large for decades, human rights defenders say that the city has always known the two bound motives of vigilantes: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling for the first time allowed black citizens to vote for the primary, which was to take place that summer.
In about the same election, according to the FBI, a black user, Roger Malcolm, stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, in a fight, apparently because of a woman.
Brooks says that, according to rumors that hester was sleeping with Malcolm Dorothy's wife, and that the baby she was supposed to have wasn't from her husband.
According to FBI reports, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a major white landowner, paid $600 bail to get Malcolm out of prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But when they drove out of prison and drove to Morse Ford Bridge, a crowd of vigilantes surrounded the car.
"It turns out that Harrison's murder was organized and commanded," this is the conclusion of an FBI report.
"It is also clear that there was a conspiracy between state and city law enforcement agencies, which not only took part in the murders, but also destroyed the evidence and concealed the identity of the witnesses."
Brooks calls it shorter.
"It was an attempt on electoral rights," he says.
"They've all been killed to send a signal to the blacks in town: if you register and vote, you'll be the same."
For almost ten years, Cassandra Green has been running an annual play replicating that lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is visible, he captures the audience and talks about the profound racism that many would like to believe is no longer present in America.
It's hard to see and even harder to turn away, but Green thinks that's what matters.
"We don't want to talk about the Lynch courts because they show us our own uglyness," she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you unless you hear me or hear what I've been through."
The rehearsals of this year's play began in June, and on the first day, almost 30 actors - a dozen whites, the rest of them black - gathered in the room and listened to an over-the-year review of the play.
Wade Marbo was director with Green.
He has played the role of chief member of the clan for several years, but he says the role has never been easier.
"I think I'm dirty because it's not the man I am," Marbo says.
"But I think it's very important to remember this story because we don't want to go back to that time."
In the room, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascon, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, are repeating their roles.
Spectacle begins with Malcolm, angry that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said nigga, get out of my house!"
Razcon screams back.
It's blowing.
And at the same time, all (at least all black actors) laugh.
Green laughs louder than anyone.
"What's the matter?" Asks Ascon.
He's concerned and embarrassed.
Am I overplaying?
"No," says Green through laughter.
"I just don't think the whites said 'nigga' back then."
"Yes, yes," laughs one of the black performers.
"You've got to get a hard 'r'."
And the energy in the room is also changing: the discomfort is changing from a sense of partnership.
Everyone has to do the right thing, not just for the play, but for the memory of the four dead.
The scene starts over.
This time, when Rascon says the "N" word, it gets clear and sharp.
No one laughs.
The show ends cruelly and quickly.
Screams, shots, and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands over the actors' bodies and sings the sad song of Billy Holiday "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is interrupted through the word.
A hundred yards from it, half a hundred viewers wipe their tears and sweat from their eyes.
There are almost equal numbers of blacks and whites among the audience.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York, to see the show; many live close by.
They had all endured Georgia's heavy perfume for almost eight hours while Brooks took them to a pilgrimage to Malcolm and Dorsey's graves.
Until then, the murders remained only a story, but now that they're standing in the same place where people were lynching, it seems that their ghosts are in the air.
When the last note of the song subsides, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
Kids bend over to their heads, touch blood paint and fixed bodies and whisper something to each other.
"They're not really dead," a little boy mutters like he's trying to remind himself.
In a few minutes, Green thanks the audience, and suddenly it's over.
Actors drop ropes off their necks and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, the man in the suit who played the main doll-clan.
Nick Rascona hugs two other actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional load of the play finally hit him.
"It's okay," whispers one of the women.
"We know you have a good heart.
You had reason to do so."
Later, the audience sits down for dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta has a lively discussion with the black couple they just met.
Denise Daplinski has difficulty finding words to describe how she feels after the performance.
"It's hard to listen to those horrible, horrible words, and actions... people who look like you, and who do it because they look like you," she says.
"After that, I think lynchings are still happening," she adds, "only now it's called what the police are shooting."
In the other corner of the room, Tyrone Brooks took over the attentions, who at food remembers his work as a human rights defender.
He says he's already started planning next year's show.
"The play inspires us because it not only describes the horror of what we've been through, but also teaches us," he says.
'Cause if you don't learn from it, it could happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it."
