New test results for assessing the age of asylum-seekers in Sweden published
Recent tests of asylum-seekers in Sweden, who had been subjected to a new method of medical assessment of age, showed that more than 80 per cent of those tested had been assessed as over 18 years of age, but not all trusted the accuracy of those results.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicalverket) began testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the assessment of age in the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationverket) was criticized for not being able to determine the real age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
So far, Migrationverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published 2,481 tests between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty per cent (2002) of the testees were assessed as 18 years or older, and in another 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency estimated that the tester was "probably 18 years or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that a person was "probably under 18".
Tests are conducted only when the age of the person is in doubt.
According to Johan Gueranson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent with those of the past months.
"We don't see much difference with the statistics of the past months, the numbers are quite appropriate," he said to The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which people were assessed as having reached the age of 18 did not necessarily indicate that asylum-seekers had lied about their age.
In May, the agency released 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases "most likely the age of the test is 18 years or more".
However, after examining 581 published results, the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases a person had openly declared that he was 18 years old.
The method of conducting a medical assessment of age, which consists of an X-ray of the wisdom teeth and a tomography of the knee joints for examination by dentists and X-rayers, has also been criticized in some instances.
One of the skeptics is an endocrinologist from the Carolyn Institute, Claude Marcus, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of humans to determine whether they have passed through puberty before or after normal maturity.
"I had reason to think about it, and I don't think it's necessary to use the measurement methods that are being used now.
The biological age is thus very inaccurate.
If we can't identify him with certainty, we shouldn't pretend we can," he said to Metro.
Heranssen, however, of the Forensic Medicine Agency, argued in favour of the accuracy of the tests: "In general, the risk of mistaking a child as an adult is small.
We face the greatest risk when a person is about 18, in which case he is about 10 per cent."
