Judges are asked to protect themselves from presidents.
On behalf of Vladimir Putin, the Presidential Council for Human Rights (CHR) has drawn up proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes that the powers of the presidents of the courts be limited and that their election be established.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the Human Rights Council wishes to introduce special districts that will not be attached to the administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also submit proposals in the context of a presidential commission.
The HRC has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
The HRC carried out this work on behalf of Vladimir Putin of 3 January 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with the Council.
At a meeting with the board on 8 December 2016, some cases of judicial arbitrariness were discussed, as were the problems of public control in detention facilities (see JO of 9 December).
The outcome of the HRC ' s work was 25 proposals, both concerning the independence of judges and the detection of miscarriages of justice, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of court presidents to enhance the independence of the remaining judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge has successfully passed the competition and has received the support of the judicial community, the HRC considers that the president of the court should present him for appointment without the right to refuse, as the law now permits.
It is also proposed that the President be denied the right to allocate cases to judges.
It's allowed by experts, it can be a specially written computer program.
The HRC also considers that the President is not entitled to "predict the judge's qualifications, initiate disciplinary action against him or her, and decide on the establishment of additional material payments".
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to "the election of the Presidents of the Courts by the judges themselves" and "to give them powers for a relatively short period of time, with mandatory rotation".
All presidents of the courts (from republican to district) are now appointed by the President for six years on the proposal of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the HRC proposes to re-organize appeals and cassation in the ordinary courts.
Their structure is now linked to the administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC states that "it is necessary to ensure that individual courts of appeal and cassation are organized not at the level of the regional judicial bodies in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts".
Experts have adopted the practice of arbitral tribunals.
They have "judicial districts" that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but which thus guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who find it difficult to use "telephone law".
The HRC ' s justices of the peace propose that the people ' s assessors be strengthened to deal with certain "civil and administrative cases".
For example, deprivation of parental rights, reinstatement, protection of honour and dignity, deprivation of driving permits, etc.
"These are only our proposals," explained a member of the HRC, a retired judge of the Constitutional Court, Tamara Morszhakova.
She also recalled that the President ' s mandate applied not only to the HRC but also to the Supreme Court (SC), which had not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the Armed Forces to carry out its task (with the co-execution of the Gender and Human Rights Commissioner in the Russian Federation).
To report to Vladimir Putin on the effectiveness of the Russian Federation ' s independence of justice, the Chairman of the Armed Forces of Vyacheslav Lebedev is due before 1 September.
Living a tall life: a semi-elegance and clever designer move turned this little apartment in Earl's Court into a spacious home.
Joan Lee, a former real estate banker, moved from a spacious house in Nightsbridge to an apartment in Earl's Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the first floor of a nice, modeled, Queen Anne-style house, and the new design is supported by the fact that Joan didn't pack her things and move again.
"I used to live with my ex in Nightsbridge in a much larger area," Joan says.
"I was looking for something comparable for my money.
They showed me this apartment in Earl's Court, and there were just as high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered a price on the same day."
Since the first review, an apartment of 1,000 square feet has undergone a complete renovation.
Initially, it was an apartment with one bedroom of complex planning – to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add space to store things and half-seats to make the most of the benefits from the generous ceiling height.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands," she says.
To that end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the architectural design studio "Duck & Shed" in Notting Hill to use the 12.5-foot ceiling and create a housing that would not only be a successful project but would be good for Joan.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms one above the other, so the architectural task was to create a semi-estate where one could stand at full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to deal with the briff.
"The work with steel structures is very complicated," he explains.
"We had to set up rooms so that they could be placed above each other, and we didn't have to bend.
It was not just necessary to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed to use the spaces from above and from below."
This decision allowed Erfan to have two full-sized rooms one above the other in the space – and a lot more interesting.
From the semi-ethage through the vintage copper light window of "Retrovius", a view of the gorgeous living room below is opened.
Mirror furniture with gold trim, silver accents, and vintage lighting devices from Serge Mui are setting up the design style.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding display, spaciousness, and light.
The short corridor is covered with mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, the mirror panel looks like a window to another room.
At the entrance, the mirror cabinets serve to store all of Joan's dishes.
In order to create a sense of greater luxury, the beauty of the living room can block the kitchen when it is not used.
There's nothing new in the emerging kitchens.
The unique thing about this kitchen is that it's a moving door upstairs, like in a garage.
"The art of engineering has been used here," Ehrfan tells us about a steel-armed wood-fibre shield door.
"It's equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily."
Thanks to the prudent use of space and storage areas, Joan received an additional 16 square metres, an additional bedroom and improved layout.
"In the end, the floor space is exactly what you're going to sell, that is, what your real estate is valued by," says Erfan.
"Breakingly speaking, the real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the floor space."
Here, they were able to increase the floor area by using quality materials that gave luxury space.
" Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection to the house," says Erfan.
"No one falls in love with the wiring in the walls.
It is important, but it does not touch the strings of our hearts."
It's a sign that, at the expense of a good design and an enlarged meter, the apartment can turn from something normal to something amazing.
Actually, like Joan, you can decide to stay.
The Government approved the establishment of a cultural policy commission
The Russian Government has approved the establishment of a commission on State cultural policy.
The relevant decree has been published on the Government ' s website.
According to the document, the main task of the commission would be to formulate and adjust strategic approaches to cultural policy implementation.
The Commission will also draft a cultural policy strategy, clarify tasks and prepare new programmes for its implementation.
The head of the Commission has been appointed Vice-President of the Government of the Russian Federation.
The composition of the commission will be approved separately.
The Prime Minister of the Russian Federation, Dmitry Medvedev, approved in 2016 a plan for the implementation of the State cultural policy strategy until 2030.
The plan includes 193 measures and measures to increase the influence of Russian culture in other countries, preserve a single cultural space and cultural heritage, and will contribute to the creation of conditions for the development of culture in the country.
Inflation in G20 countries dropped to an eight-year minimum
The rise in consumer prices in G20 countries has fallen to the lowest levels in the past eight years, reports The Wall Street Journal with reference to data from the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
OECD estimates that inflation in June 2016 was 2 per cent - lower in October 2009, when the price growth index reached 1.7 per cent.
Rosstat previously reported a 0.1 per cent decline in the consumer price index in Russia.
The agency thus recorded the first week of deflation in 2017.
The inflation rate in Russia is estimated at 4.1 per cent by the Ministry of Finance.
The Ministry of Economy, however, believes that the target has already been achieved, according to the agency ' s version, at 4 per cent.
