The brothers are fighting for a real estate empire worth more than $500 million.
Two brothers are fighting for one of Victoria's largest real estate empires, worth more than $500 million, 40 years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
Former director of Carlton's football club and developer Colin de Lutis live in Turak Palace three doors from his younger brother Paul, who sued him in the Supreme Court for the division of property and assets.
Paul wants to leave the family business since 2014, but the Supreme Court is still in a violent dispute about the terms of divorce.
Together with their mother Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, bought since their family bought a shop on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew into a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the De Lutis family's property list includes today's office buildings, building sites in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Golden Bank and Mount Buller, and shopping centres in the suburbs.
In agreement with Colin's late father, whom Paul describes as "the main driving force and dominant person" of the De Lutis family, the De Lutis family owns about two thirds of the company's assets and Paul owns about one third.
According to the court, Colin's property is 316 million and Paul's 176 million.
The division of property and money has become a stumbling block for Paul.
"The division offered by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of the property," he wrote in his first statement in 2015.
Last Friday, after several unsuccessful reconciliation attempts, the first hearings in the Supreme Court were held.
The brothers are now arguing about who will control the existing business - from which Paul believes Colin has ruled it out.
Colin claims that this is not the case, but accuses Paul of incompetent management of certain objects.
In Colin's testimony at the beginning of the trial, he says he looks forward to a resolution of the dispute.
"My Italian roots make me consider my family a top priority," he wrote.
Court costs are rising as a snowball: hundreds of pages of testimony, e-mails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Kramer have been added to the case; both parties have brought in the best-known lawyers, including King's Counsel Allan Meyers, and the best cooks.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late wife, Luigi, were immigrants from Italy; since the late 1950s, they have operated dairy bars and gastronoms, and in the early 1970s they bought a store in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood where Colin opened the first family jeans store.
Colin says he started Westco when he was "in the last grade of the school, and Paul was then a boy (about 10 years old).
Anna De Lutis says that he and Luigi, who died in 2012, were hoping to transfer their possessions to their sons without conflict.
"Louigi often told me he didn't want his brothers to go to trial," she wrote.
Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of De Lutis's group of companies; Colina says that Mark got 10 million when he left the business and Luke 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were "displeased with the financial conditions of their office".
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the board of directors of the AFL club and, according to Eddie McGir's 2015 biography, the best friend of the TV star.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin replied, a text message that stated that, since the case had not yet been tried, "I really have nothing to say."
"I'm very, very sorry that my brother Paul decided to sue me and talk in court about our family's name," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin testified that he was trying to satisfy his brother's demands.
"Our father wouldn't want to see Paul and I arguing in court," he said, adding that "we still hope to resolve the conflict."
Friday, that hope seems to have been dispelled.
"Our case will soon be decided by a court of law," said Colin.
The new head of Trump's office is planning to limit the flow of information to the President.
Others tried to do so and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
Then he'll be the first.
Politicalo reports that the new Chief of the White House is planning to limit the flow of information to President Trump, including news reports from the media, hoping to keep the Chief calm.
That's what reporter Josh Dawsey says.
"At a meeting that the new White House Chief of Staff, John F. Kelly, held with the management of the office on his first day of work, he identified the main problem in the White House under President Donald Trump, which he hopes to solve: bad channels of information to the President."
Kelly told the staff that the information had to go through it -- paper or briefings -- because the president would be better off making decisions if he got the right information.
Kelly's diagnosis is completely correct, but others have already failed in trying to calm Trump by tracking the flow of information to him.
President Trump's relationship with television began decades ago - and now that he's in the White House, his habit of watching TV is still strong.
"When Trump, as a candidate, resented the unfair coverage of the campaign, it was useful to show him that he had received fair coverage in publications that could have been re-converted," said Sam Nanberg, a former Electoral Staff Counsellor, in February.
Tara Palmery then wrote in "Policio" that "in the words of six former election staff members, in order to control Trump's habit of tweeting, it was necessary to make sure that the information that came to him personally contained a constant stream of praise."
Okay.
But the idea that Trump's habit of tweeting has ever been "controlled" is ridiculous.
Maybe these election staff members know something we don't know -- for example, if it weren't for them, Trump's tweet would have been even more provocative.
We may never know about the tweets Trump didn't publish.
If his staff kept him out of trouble at least a few times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has ever been able to keep Trump from pouring oil into the fire.
Part of the problem is that in the White House divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to push their subpoena by giving Trump material - reliable or not - that confirms their views.
"Politico"--this is exactly the story-- wrote in May about the counselor's tendency to constantly give the president questionable information.
Here's an example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"The current and former Trump staff say Trump can react very sharply to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds out who was behind them.
This happened at the end of February, when someone printed out an article from GotNews.com to the president, Charles C. Johnson's Internet proprietor's website, in which Katie Welsch's deputy chief of staff was accused of being behind the leaks in the White House.
It doesn't matter that Johnson's forever trapped on Twitter for his aggressive behavior, that he didn't present specific facts, or that in the past he started false accusations and then turned them down.
Trump read the article and started asking staff about Welch."
Goldmacher adds that then Chief of Staff Rains Pribus and Secretary of the Rob Porter Office "tryed to build a system to control and document the flow of the papers that Trump receives."
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly's trying to do the same.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Pribus, but Trump still has impulsive nature, and his associates are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly's task very difficult.
The Tumen Prosecutor ' s Office is fighting an HIV dissident.
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office challenged the decision of the Kalinin Ra ' sud Tümeni, who had discontinued the criminal case against a local woman whose daughter had died of HIV.
As a result, the child is said to have died because the mother is an HIV dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court acquitted her of her responsibility for reconciliation with the injured father.
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished in order not to set a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against a Tümeni resident was brought under article 109, paragraph 1, of the Criminal Code (causing death by negligence) in April, after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection.
According to the Public Prosecutor ' s Office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
"The woman has not been treated herself and has refused to treat her daughter, believing that there is no HIV infection," explained in the Office of the Prosecutor of the Tumen Region.
The criminal case was brought before the Kalininsk Raisud Tümeni, who decided on 25 July to discontinue it.
The father of the deceased girl filed a request to do so, explaining that "he has asked his wife, has no claims against her, has made amends and has apologized".
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office did not accept the court ' s decision and appealed, demanding that the decision to dismiss the case be withdrawn and sent to a new hearing.
The girl died, and it's impossible to make amends for the crime.
The HIV-positive mother, contrary to the doctors' advice, refused to examine the baby and treat her with a dangerous infection," reported to the Public Prosecutor's Office.
In the view of the oversight body, she should be punished, otherwise her example would be followed by other HIV-dissidents.
According to the Thai AIDS Centre, about 12 HIV-positive children in Tumen province are currently not receiving medical care because of parental refusal.
"This situation has already improved - during the year of work of the special group, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat their children for HIV, changed their minds - allowed for diagnostics, started taking medications," reported Elena Loseva, a spokesman for the AIDS Centre.
She said that it was impossible to legislate on parents and that not all HIV-positive children could be detected - mothers were not allowed to examine them, were hiding, were running away with children from hospitals.
What are the dangers of HIV dissidents?
At the end of last year, Peterburg social scientists presented the results of Russia's first study of the so-called HIV dissident movement.
HIV dissidents are referred to as people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Health professionals and AIDS service activists in the NPOs refer to such attitudes as anti-medical, and they see their dissemination as a serious threat.
The terrible photo shoot, which ended in tragedy, took place on Thursday, 3 August, at the Greek railway station in Hmelnitsky.
A fun company of drunk young people walked over the railway tracks, where a freight train was just standing.
One of the friends had the idea of making a glamorous selfie on the roof of the car, and they told FACTAM in the police communications sector in Khmelnitsky province.
The guy started coming down from the bridge to the train, but due to his negligence, he stuck himself on the power line and got electrocuted instantly.
Fortunately, this case was reported to the station's dispatcher, who immediately called an emergency room.
Prior to the arrival of the doctors, the victim was transferred to a safe place and then hospitalized in the burning section of the Khmelnitsky Regional Clinical Hospital.
Men were diagnosed with torso burns from 1 to 2 degrees.
His condition is now assessed by doctors as stable.
The law enforcement community recalls that extreme selfies on the rooftops of multi-purposes, bridges, and transport are becoming increasingly popular in recent times.
The police call on people to be vigilant and to avoid such photographs, especially among children and adolescents.
