Similarity: The artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of the hall at the Friedman Gallery in New York City, people's faces hang from the ceiling on wire - white, black and brown, all of them incredibly similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheek swabs and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent clippings from Fort Levenworth Prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving 35 years for a famous broadcast of confidential diplomatic telegrams on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibit, which opened on 2 August, is called "A resemblance."
This is the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey Harborg, whose art unites technology, information technology and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and a famous dissident, who Barack Obama reduced his sentence only three days before his presidency ended.
By analysing the DNA from Manning using a computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of people who might have such a genome, Dewey Harborg created a deep, though difficult, manifesto not only about the plasticity of DNA data - different ways of interpreting them and the inert determinism of these interpretations - but also the notion of identity.
Manning, who was born with the name Bradley Edward, but has been openly saying since she was a teenager that she thinks she's a woman, was sentenced in 2013 to 20 episodes, including six violations of the Spy Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her photos in prison were inaccessible, so only one photograph of her was known: a grainy black and white selfie, in which Manning, in a platinum shade of wig, was clearly uncomfortable, sitting behind the wheel of the car; with this photograph, she was associated.
In 2015, Dewey Harborg successfully completed his 2012 project "Vision of Strangers".
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as butters and gums, drawing DNA out of this garbage and creating images of what these people might look like.
And then she got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted a portrait to illustrate the article," explained Dewey Hagborg at the preliminary showing of a new press exhibit.
At the time, Chelsea could not be visited and photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait of her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her prison muse became pen pals and exchanged several letters for two years.
They even wrote a book of Comic books called "Sacred Images," illustrated by Shauli Canungo, who illustrated how the president would ease Chelsea's punishment in the future and she would be able to attend the exhibition in person.
Obama's decision to release Manning just a few days after the book was released was a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a military prison in Kansas.
There's something deep and powerful about the exhibition opening now that Donald Trump is declaring war on people who reveal secret information in the government and inventing new ways to fuel the hostility he's supposed to mitigate on Twitter.
When Dewey Harborg was asked about the timing of all this, she said, "Nothing happens randomly."
In an artist's statement written on the wall of the Gallery, Manning's huge signature (with a heart at the bottom instead of a point above "i" in her name) calls for an end to "automatic separation based on sex, race, sexual orientation and culture".
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar made of C, G and A pencils.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the scientific artist expresses in a subtle way), Dewey Harborg hoped to show how we all look at each other, at least in terms of our biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome does not determine what we are, how open genetic data is for interpretation, and how subjective it is," Dewey Harborg said; her 2007 video work, "Lady Memory," is also posted here.
"This DNA can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of these stories are here."
The last part of the show in the same room is the novel mentioned above in the comic books.
It's got Manning in King Kong style showing up over the U.S. Correctional Kazarm building with a loudspeaker in his hand.
"If they kill your speech, they win," it says there.
"So don't ever shut up."
"This is a direct quote from the letter she wrote me," says the artist welcoming us from Philadelphia.
"I still have the creeps when I talk about it."
Manning hasn't seen the exhibition in person - as it was seen in the comic books - but when she comes, she'll be welcomed by the masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulations, gathered like a crowd of protesters.
It's also intentional, like everyone at the exhibition up to the height (5'2, Manning's height), where the pencil was drawn with genetic gaplags.
"I would have put them on the walls earlier, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people," Dewey Harborg says about portraits.
"I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea, like the movement behind her release."
