Startups that will help your company not become another Uber
Aimee Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction of her e-commerce startup staff, but the polls weren't working.
The answers were often vague, useless, or, worse, insincere.
Even though she promised anonymity, some staff members did not trust the process.
"He was never consistent and objective," Errett said, managing a 75-person company based in San Francisco, Madison Reed, which is involved in e-commerce in the field of hair care.
It therefore sought the assistance of third parties.
A new type of start-up is now emerging in the area of staff management, which helps companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software, the purpose of which is to measure the involvement of staff members, they enable companies to conduct rapid interviews, address certain teams and demographic groups, offer staff anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases allow informants to skip the top management and address the directorate directly.
"We now have tools such as Strava and Fitbit to monitor health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Glint startup from Redwood City, whose analytical programs are used by companies to measure employee involvement.
Herrett explained that she had gained a better understanding of what her staff thought and felt in three years of using the Glint.
In addition to the rapid interviews and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a warmer map of the company and shows in graphic form which units have more complaints and which managers have low approval ratings, which allows it to understand why.
Companies realize a little bit that they need to control the workplace, otherwise they will become the next Uber who was involved in the scandal when a former employee posted a post on a blog describing an aggressive environment in which those who complained were punished.
For startups like "Glint", it's a desire to control the situation - the opportunity for profitable business.
The online portal "Let's Talk About Pay" on financial technology estimates that the global governance, regulatory and conformity industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
"Convercent" from Denver, Colorado, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year, against the backdrop of a decline in Uber's reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber has recently appeared among clients.
Like "Glint", "Convercent" allows companies to send individually commissioned interviews of staff, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows staff to report misconduct.
And if the top manager is involved, the complaints go straight to the directorate.
"The Court of Public Opinion seized power from the inspectors," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is mistreating employees or being unethical, even if the inspector does not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by clients, staff departures and lawsuits, Quinlan informed.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with over 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, has used Convercent for over a year to make sure that staff are aware of the rules and procedures and to offer a simple way of going to the company's head office.
In the past, if a staff member wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for a telephone number or a head office e-mail, file a formal complaint and hope that she would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and awkward experience, reported James Vitrano, head of Ruby Tuesday's legal department, who said that there was no normal way to follow up staff complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harasment, and unfair pay – can be found and dealt with more quickly.
"I can draw closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the staff situation," said Vitrano, who runs the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
"And we protect our shareholders from litigation with staff."
According to Quinland, companies began to take more seriously the ethics, values and involvement of employees in 2002, after Arthur Andersen's accounting firm collapsed due to ethical irregularities as a result of Dela Enron.
But it was only when "social networks became widespread" that companies realized that they would not be able to keep their dirty underwear from viral distribution online.
"Before using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both "Glint" and "Convercent" offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for using their products.
It's a business model and an opportunity approved by venture investors who supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
"Glint" received $10 million in November from Bessemmer Vienna Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing volume of research shows that today's employees expect more of their jobs than they did before.
In markets with strong competition, such as the Silicon Valley, high wages, and interesting projects, that's just the minimum.
The staff want to feel that they are accepted and valued and that they devote their time to the company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy working for a company, feel that they are being heard, and that the work they do is working, they're trying more to make such a company a success," says Nina McQueen, vice president for global benefits and staff satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors earn income when companies in their portfolio do well; companies do well when employees are loyal and involved.
If the analysis tools of a third party promise to increase the loyalty and involvement of the staff, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to cultural experts in the workplace, it is important to have data on the involvement of employees.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can give the impression that change is coming.
And if change does not occur quickly enough or at all, frustration may develop and staff will lose interest.
"If you're gonna ask 4,000 offers, you should be ready to have 4,000 conversations," says Russell Rat, president of the consulting firm Kotter International, who had to see companies making a mistake relying too much on data collection.
"Because if you don't go to the end, the staff will wonder, "Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care?"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly staff interviews, is in a position to take action on the same day when someone reports the problem through the Glint.
And after collecting feedback from employees, disgruntled decision-making and quality of communication, she was able to restructure several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long term it will be able to better retain staff in an industry known for high turnover.
"If you do not try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people," said Vitrano.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
