The White House bill cost taxpayers thousands of dollars.
According to the military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House's decision last month to bring a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One", when the president is on board, became the central feature of a White House event on July 17, which featured American construction programmes.
President Donald Trump, Vice-President Mike Pence, and the White House's top officials examined technological products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, which took place in Connecticut, was placed near a boat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a cargo truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1) of the helicopter management department, the White House Military Department ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or FRAGO, only 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an "unusual" event.
"I just wanted you to know that you are aware because this is an unusual, widely publicized event," wrote Commander HMX-1 in an e-mail to his superior, the first deputy aviation chief of the Marine Corps, the day before the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on 17 July to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and remain there until the lawn was released between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return flight in accordance with restrictions on working hours.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, while the unit ' s guards remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records obtained by the magazine "TIME" whether a second crew was ultimately required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 specified whether the activity was in conflict with the regulation.
"We asked, among other things, whether it was a violation of Hatch's law, and we were told that it wasn't," the commander wrote.
"You don't seem to have anywhere to go," the deputy chief replied.
The White House was declared an official event, and Hatch's law was not applicable to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the reform of health care, which was then being drafted in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as "Marine One" and "Air Force One" for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's unusual to ask for them alone in the interest of photo possibility.
Trump was already the subject of discussions in February, when the President's plane went in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was full of complaints about the use of the President's plane by his predecessor.
"The White House is thrilled to see "America made", which presented products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," said Lindsay Walters, Deputy Press Secretary of the White House.
HMX-1 units often perform training flights around the Washington agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the President of the United States to transport to the White House to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings outside the White House.
According to an official, the flight performed for the America-made event was credited to the crew for the required training flights in a month.
The unit ' s helicopters also flew 11 additional hours on that day as part of "non-presidential support tasks".
According to the White House, the taxpayers were not paid for any of the other items presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky stated that the company had not taken part in a helicopter demonstration on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not account for the presidential flight budget, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Department of Defense's hourly rate for the 2017 fiscal year, the Department of Defense's VH-3D rate is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit ' s records show that the aircraft ' s time in the air was 30 minutes each way from its base at the Kuantico Marine Base in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than that.
"The calculation of the value for taxpayers based on the estimated rate of reimbursement is entirely wrong," Walters says.
"These indicative rates include personnel, services and many other irreversible costs that are included in annual allocations."
According to a study conducted by RAND in 2015, the rates of reimbursement do not include the cost of personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, Sean Spyser, former White House spokesperson, was defending the use of a helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to demonstrate this week the things that have been done in America," said Spicer.
"And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to create.
Therefore, of course, it is entirely appropriate to draw attention to this."
It wasn't clear if Trump interacted with the chopper by examining the South Lawn during the event, but he definitely sat in the driver's seat in a fire truck.
Within the White House, Trump approached Sikorsky, making a press joke about his own fleet of products.
"I know well "Sikorsky," said the president. "I have three of them."
